<section label="linsys-exercises">
	<title>Exercises</title>

	<exercises label="linsys-concept-quiz">
		<title><e component="emoji">💡</e> Conceptual Quiz</title>
		
		<aside>
			<title>Abbreviations</title>
			<tabular>
				<col width="10%" />
				<col width="90%" />
				<row>
					<cell><p><em>DE</em></p></cell>
					<cell><em>Differential Equation</em></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell><p><em>IVP</em></p></cell>
					<cell><em>Initial Value Problem</em></cell>
				</row>
			</tabular>
		</aside>

		<exercise label="linsys-cq">
			<title>True-False</title>

			<task label="linsys-cq-1">
				<title><e component="emoji">📖❓</e>  Which Variable Drives Which?</title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Consider the system:
					</p>
					<md>
						<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt} \amp = x - y</mrow>
						<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt} \amp = -2y</mrow>
					</md>
					<p>
						Select all true statements:
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices randomize="yes">
					<choice correct="no">
						<statement><p><m>x</m> evolves independently of <m>y</m>.</p></statement>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="no">
						<statement><p><m>y</m> depends on <m>x</m>.</p></statement>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="no">
						<statement><p>This is an uncoupled system.</p></statement>
						<feedback><p>Not quite — notice that <m>y</m> shows up in the <m>dx/dt</m> equation.</p></feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement><p>You must solve for <m>y</m> before you can solve for <m>x</m>.</p></statement>
						<feedback><p>Yes — solve <m>y</m> first (it is independent), then use it to solve for <m>x</m>.</p></feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>

			<task label="linsys-cq-2">
				<title>Interdependence</title>
				<statement>What makes a system fully coupled? How does that affect how we approach the problem?</statement>
			</task>

			<task label="linsys-cq-3">
				<title><e component="emoji">📖❓</e>  Classify the System</title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Match each system to the correct classification.
					</p>
					<p>
						<em>Assume both <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are functions of <m>t</m>.</em>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
					Systems are classified by whether variables influence each other and how they do so. Look for dependencies in the right-hand sides.
					</p>
				</feedback>
				<cardsort>
					<match>
						<premise><md><mrow>x' \amp = x,</mrow> <mrow>y' \amp = y</mrow></md></premise>
						<premise><md><mrow>x' \amp = \cos(t),</mrow> <mrow>y' \amp = y</mrow></md></premise>
						<response>Uncoupled</response>
					</match>
					<match>
						<premise><md><mrow>x' \amp = x,</mrow> <mrow>y' \amp = x + y</mrow></md></premise>
						<premise><md><mrow>x' \amp = x,</mrow> <mrow>y' \amp = t + x</mrow></md></premise>
						<response>Partially Coupled</response>
					</match>
					<match>
						<premise><md><mrow>x' \amp = x + y,</mrow> <mrow>y' \amp = x - y</mrow></md></premise>
						<response>Fully Coupled</response>
					</match>
				</cardsort>
			</task>

			<task label="linsys-cq-4">
				<title><e component="emoji">📖❓</e>  Identifying Features</title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Select all statements that are true about partially coupled systems.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices randomize="yes" multiple-correct="yes">
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement><p>One equation is independent and can be solved first.</p></statement>
						<feedback><p>Yes, this is a defining feature of partial coupling.</p></feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement><p>Both equations must be solved simultaneously.</p></statement>
						<feedback><p>No, only fully coupled systems require that.</p></feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement><p>The dependent equation uses the solution of the independent one.</p></statement>
						<feedback><p>Exactly. You substitute <m>x(t)</m> into the second equation to solve for <m>y(t)</m>.</p></feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement><p>Partial coupling means both variables evolve independently.</p></statement>
						<feedback><p>That describes an uncoupled system, not a partially coupled one.</p></feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement><p>Only one of the equations involves both variables.</p></statement>
						<feedback><p>Correct. The coupling only appears in one direction.</p></feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement><p>The second variable can be solved without knowing the first.</p></statement>
						<feedback><p>Nope, you need <m>x(t)</m> to solve for <m>y(t)</m>.</p></feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>

			<task label="linsys-cq-5">
				<title><e component="emoji">📖❓</e>  Select the True Statements</title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Which of the following statements are true for the system:
						<md>
							<mrow> \frac{dx}{dt} \amp = -x + 1 </mrow>
							<mrow> \frac{dy}{dt} \amp = -2y </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices randomize="yes" multiple-correct="yes">
					<choice correct="no">
						<statement>The rate of change of <m>x</m> depends on <m>y</m>.</statement>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>The variable <m>x</m> has no effect on how <m>y</m> changes.</statement>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>The rate of change of <m>y</m> depends only on <m>y</m>.</statement>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="no">
						<statement>This is an example of a coupled system.</statement>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="no">
						<statement>This system has two independent variables.</statement>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>

			<task label="linsys-cq-6">
				<title><e component="emoji">📖❓</e>  Independent Solutions</title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						In an uncoupled system, how do we find the solution for the whole system?
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices randomize="yes">
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement><p>Solve each equation separately, then combine the answers into a pair <m>(x(t), y(t))</m>.</p></statement>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="no">
						<statement><p>Rewrite the system as a second-order equation for just one variable.</p></statement>
						<feedback><p>You could do this in some cases, but for uncoupled systems, it's simpler to solve each one directly.</p></feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="no">
						<statement><p>Use Euler's Method only — they cannot be solved exactly.</p></statement>
						<feedback><p>Uncoupled systems are straightforward to solve exactly.</p></feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>

			<solution>
				<ol>
					<li>
						<p>Task 1: You must solve for <m>y</m> before you can solve for <m>x</m>. The equation for <m>y</m> is independent (contains only <m>y</m>), while the equation for <m>x</m> depends on <m>y</m>, making this a partially coupled system.</p>
					</li>
					<li>
						<p>Task 2: A fully coupled system is one where both equations contain both variables, requiring simultaneous solution. In such systems, neither equation can be solved independently—you must solve them together using methods like elimination, substitution, or matrix techniques.</p>
					</li>
					<li>
						<p>Task 3: Uncoupled systems have equations that each depend on only one variable (e.g., <m>x' = x, y' = y</m> or <m>x' = \cos(t), y' = y</m>). Partially coupled systems have one independent equation and one dependent equation (e.g., <m>x' = x, y' = x + y</m>). Fully coupled systems have both equations depending on both variables (e.g., <m>x' = x + y, y' = x - y</m>).</p>
					</li>
					<li>
						<p>Task 4: In a partially coupled system: (1) One equation is independent and can be solved first, (2) The dependent equation uses the solution of the independent one, and (3) Only one of the equations involves both variables.</p>
					</li>
					<li>
						<p>Task 5: For the system <m>dx/dt = -x + 1, dy/dt = -2y</m>, the variable <m>x</m> has no effect on how <m>y</m> changes, and the rate of change of <m>y</m> depends only on <m>y</m>. This is an uncoupled system.</p>
					</li>
					<li>
						<p>Task 6: For an uncoupled system, solve each equation separately, then combine the answers into a pair <m>(x(t), y(t))</m>.</p>
					</li>
				</ol>
			</solution>
			<answer>
				<p>1) Solve <m>y</m> first. 2) Fully coupled = both equations contain both variables; must solve simultaneously. 3) Match: uncoupled (separate variables), partially coupled (one depends on other), fully coupled (both depend on both). 4) One independent equation, one dependent. 5) <m>y</m> is independent of <m>x</m>. 6) Solve separately and combine.</p>
			</answer>

		</exercise>
	</exercises>

	<exercises label="linsys-problems-main">
		<title><e component="emoji">✍🏻</e> Problems </title>

		<exercisegroup>
			<title>The Eigenvalue Method</title>

			<introduction>
				<p>
					Practice the eigenvalue method from <xref ref="solving-linear-systems" text="title"/>: find eigenvalues and eigenvectors, build general solutions, and classify the phase portrait using <xref ref="eigenvalues-and-phase-portraits" text="title"/>.
				</p>
			</introduction>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of
						<m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						Solve <m>\det(A - rI) = 0</m>:
						<md>
							\det\begin{bmatrix} 4-r \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 3-r \end{bmatrix} = (4-r)(3-r) - 2 = r^2 - 7r + 10 = (r-2)(r-5)
						</md>
						so <m>r_1 = 2</m> and <m>r_2 = 5</m>.
					</p>
					<p>
						For <m>r_1 = 2</m>: <m>(A - 2I)\vec{v} = 0</m> gives <m>2v_1 + 2v_2 = 0</m>, so <m>v_2 = -v_1</m> and <m>\vec{v}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
					</p>
					<p>
						For <m>r_2 = 5</m>: <m>(A - 5I)\vec{v} = 0</m> gives <m>-v_1 + 2v_2 = 0</m>, so <m>v_1 = 2v_2</m> and <m>\vec{v}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<m>r_1 = 2</m> with <m>\vec{v}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}</m>; <m>r_2 = 5</m> with <m>\vec{v}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the general solution of the system and classify its phase portrait:
						<md>
							<mrow> \frac{dx}{dt} \amp = x + 2y </mrow>
							<mrow> \frac{dy}{dt} \amp = 3x </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						With <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>, the characteristic equation is
						<md>
							(1-r)(-r) - 6 = r^2 - r - 6 = (r-3)(r+2) = 0
						</md>
						so <m>r_1 = 3</m> and <m>r_2 = -2</m>.
					</p>
					<p>
						For <m>r_1 = 3</m>: <m>(A - 3I)\vec{v} = 0</m> gives <m>-2v_1 + 2v_2 = 0</m>, so <m>\vec{v}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
						For <m>r_2 = -2</m>: <m>(A + 2I)\vec{v} = 0</m> gives <m>3v_1 + 2v_2 = 0</m>, so <m>\vec{v}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix}</m>.
					</p>
					<p>
						The general solution is
						<md>
							\vec{X}(t) = C_1 \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} e^{3t} + C_2 \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix} e^{-2t}.
						</md>
						The eigenvalues are real with opposite signs, so the phase portrait is a <em>saddle</em>.
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<m>\vec{X}(t) = C_1 \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} e^{3t} + C_2 \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix} e^{-2t}</m>; saddle
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Solve the initial value problem
						<md>
							<mrow> \frac{dx}{dt} \amp = x + y, \amp x(0) \amp = 3, </mrow>
							<mrow> \frac{dy}{dt} \amp = 4x + y, \amp y(0) \amp = 2. </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						This is the system solved in <xref ref="ex-worked-linear-system" text="type-global"/>, whose general solution is
						<md>
							x(t) = C_1 e^{3t} + C_2 e^{-t}, \qquad y(t) = 2C_1 e^{3t} - 2C_2 e^{-t}.
						</md>
						Applying the initial conditions:
						<md>
							<mrow> C_1 + C_2 \amp = 3 </mrow>
							<mrow> 2C_1 - 2C_2 \amp = 2 </mrow>
						</md>
						The second equation gives <m>C_1 - C_2 = 1</m>; adding this to the first gives <m>2C_1 = 4</m>, so <m>C_1 = 2</m> and <m>C_2 = 1</m>. Hence
						<md>
							x(t) = 2e^{3t} + e^{-t}, \qquad y(t) = 4e^{3t} - 2e^{-t}.
						</md>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p><m>x(t) = 2e^{3t} + e^{-t},\quad y(t) = 4e^{3t} - 2e^{-t}</m></p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Find the general solution of the system and classify its phase portrait:
						<md>
							<mrow> \frac{dx}{dt} \amp = -x - 2y </mrow>
							<mrow> \frac{dy}{dt} \amp = 2x - y </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						With <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp -2 \\ 2 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, the characteristic equation is
						<md>
							(-1-r)^2 + 4 = 0 \quad\Rightarrow\quad r = -1 \pm 2i.
						</md>
					</p>
					<p>
						For <m>r = -1 + 2i</m>, <m>(A - rI)\vec{v} = 0</m> gives <m>-2i\,v_1 - 2v_2 = 0</m>, so <m>v_2 = -i\,v_1</m> and <m>\vec{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -i \end{bmatrix}</m>. Taking real and imaginary parts of <m>\vec{v}e^{(-1+2i)t}</m> gives the real general solution:
						<md>
							<mrow> x(t) \amp = e^{-t}\left( C_1 \cos(2t) + C_2 \sin(2t) \right) </mrow>
							<mrow> y(t) \amp = e^{-t}\left( C_1 \sin(2t) - C_2 \cos(2t) \right) </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
					<p>
						The eigenvalues are complex with negative real part, so the phase portrait is a <em>spiral sink</em>: trajectories loop inward as the factor <m>e^{-t}</m> decays.
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<m>x(t) = e^{-t}(C_1\cos 2t + C_2\sin 2t),\quad y(t) = e^{-t}(C_1\sin 2t - C_2\cos 2t)</m>; spiral sink
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Without solving, classify the phase portrait of a linear system whose coefficient matrix has the given eigenvalues:
						<ol marker="(a)">
							<li><m>r = -3,\ -1</m></li>
							<li><m>r = -2,\ 5</m></li>
							<li><m>r = \pm 3i</m></li>
							<li><m>r = 1 \pm 2i</m></li>
						</ol>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						Using the classification table in <xref ref="eigenvalues-and-phase-portraits" text="title"/>:
						<ol marker="(a)">
							<li>real, both negative → node (sink): all trajectories decay to the origin.</li>
							<li>real, opposite signs → saddle.</li>
							<li>purely imaginary → center: closed orbits around the origin.</li>
							<li>complex with positive real part → spiral source: trajectories loop outward.</li>
						</ol>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>(a) node (sink); (b) saddle; (c) center; (d) spiral source</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

		</exercisegroup>

		<exercisegroup>

			<introduction>
				<p>
					Solve the following systems of differential equations. The worked solutions below take a different road than the eigenvalue method: they apply the <em>Laplace transform</em> from the previous chapters to each equation, turning the system into simultaneous algebraic equations. Both methods produce the same solutions — as you work through these, notice how the exponential rates that appear are exactly the eigenvalues of each system's coefficient matrix.
				</p>
			</introduction>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
						<m>
							\left\{
							\begin{array}{rll}
								\dfrac{dx}{dt} =\amp -x+y,\amp x(0)	= 0,\\
								\dfrac{dy}{dt} =\amp 2x,	\amp y(0)	= 1.
							\end{array}
							\right.
						</m>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						We can take the LT of each DE.  The result is two algebraic equations in two unknowns <m>X(s) </m> and <m>Y(s). </m>  We will solve the equations simultaneously as shown below.
						<md>
							<mrow>  \frac{dx}{dt}	 \amp =  -x+y				\amp			\frac{dy}{dt}	\amp = 2x </mrow>
							<mrow>  \lap{\frac{dx}{dt}}	 \amp =  \lap{-x+y}		\amp	\lap{\frac{dy}{dt}}	\amp = \lap{2x} </mrow>
							<mrow>  sX(s) - x(0)	 \amp =  -\lap{x} + \lap{y}	\amp			sY(s) - y(0)	\amp = 2	\lap{x} </mrow>
							<mrow>  sX(s) - 0	 \amp =  -X(s) + Y(s)					\amp				sY(s) - 1	\amp = 2X(s) </mrow>
							<mrow>  Y(s)	 \amp =  sX(s) + X(s)					\amp						\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp							\amp s\Big[ sX(s) + X(s) \Big] - 1	 \amp =  2X(s) </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp							\amp		s^2 X(s) + sX(s) - 1	 \amp =  2X(s) </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp							\amp	s^2X(s) + sX(s) - 2X(s)	 \amp =  1 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp							\amp 		X(s) [s^2 + s - 2]	 \amp =  1 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp							\amp					X(s)	 \amp =  \frac{1}{s^2 + s - 2} </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp							\amp						 \amp =  \frac{1}{(s+2)(s-1)} </mrow>
							<mrow>  Y(s)	 \amp =  sX(s) + X(s)					\amp						\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  X(s)[s+1]					\amp						\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{(s+2)(s-1)}\cdot (s+1)	\amp						\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{s+1}{(s+2)(s-1)}			\amp						\amp  </mrow>
						</md>
						We need only take the inverse LT of each function in order to solve for the desired function <m>x(t) </m> and <m>y(t). </m> This means we will need to find a partial fraction decomposition for each.
						<md>
							<mrow>  \frac{1}{(s+2)(s-1)}	 \amp =  \frac{A}{s+2} + \frac{B}{s-1} </mrow>
							<mrow>  1	 \amp =  A(s-1) + B(s+2) </mrow>
							<mrow>  0s + 1	 \amp =  As - A + Bs + 2B </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  (A+B)s + (-A + 2B)  </mrow>
						</md>
						
						<md>
							<mrow>  A+B	 \amp =  0		\amp 	-A + 2B	\amp = 1 </mrow>
							<mrow>  B	 \amp =  -A	\amp			\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp		\amp -A + 2(-A)	 \amp =  1 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp		\amp		-3A	 \amp =  1 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp		\amp		A	 \amp =  -\frac{1}{3} </mrow>
							<mrow>  B	 \amp =  -\left( -\frac{1}{3} \right)\amp \amp </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{3}\amp			\amp  </mrow>
						</md>
						Hence,
						<md>
							<mrow>   X(s)	 \amp =  \frac{-\frac{1}{3}}{s+2} + \frac{\frac{1}{3}}{s-1}</mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{3}\left[ \frac{1}{s-1} - \frac{1}{s+2} \right]</mrow>
						</md>
						Similarly, we will find a partial fraction decomposition for<m>Y(s). </m>
						<md>
							<mrow>  \frac{s+1}{(s+2)(s-1)}	 \amp =  \frac{A}{s+2} + \frac{B}{s-1} </mrow>
							<mrow>  s + 1	 \amp =  A(s-1) + B(s+2) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  As - A + Bs + 2B </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  (A+B)s + (-A + 2B)  </mrow>
						</md>
						
						<md>
							<mrow>  A+B	 \amp =  1		\amp 	-A + 2B	\amp = 1 </mrow>
							<mrow>  B	 \amp =  1-A	\amp			\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp		\amp -A + 2(1-A)	 \amp =  1 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp		\amp	-3A + 2	 \amp =  1 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp		\amp		-3A	 \amp =  -1 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp		\amp		A	 \amp =  \frac{1}{3} </mrow>
							<mrow>  B	 \amp =  1-\left( \frac{1}{3} \right)\amp \amp </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{2}{3}\amp			\amp  </mrow>
						</md>
						Hence,
						<md>
							<mrow>   Y(s)	 \amp =  \frac{\frac{1}{3}}{s+2} + \frac{\frac{2}{3}}{s-1}</mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{3}\left[ \frac{1}{s+2} + 2\cdot \frac{1}{s-1} \right]</mrow>
						</md>
						Now we need only find the inverse LT of equations.
						<md>
							<mrow>  x(t)	 \amp =   \lap^{-1}\left\{ X(s) \right\} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{1}{3}\left[ \frac{1}{s-1} - \frac{1}{s+2} \right] \right\} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{3}\left[ \lap^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{s-1}\right\} - \lap^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{s+2}\right\} \right] </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{3}\left[ e^t - e^{-2t} \right] </mrow>
							<mrow>  y(t)	 \amp =  \lap^{-1}\left\{ Y(s) \right\} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{1}{3}\left[ \frac{1}{s+2} +2\cdot\frac{1}{s-1} \right] \right\} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{3}\left[ \lap^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{s+2}\right\} +2 \lap^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{s-1}\right\} \right] </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{3}\left[ e^{-2t} + 2e^{t} \right] </mrow>

						</md>
						This, the solution to this system is
						<md>
							<mrow>  x(t)	 \amp =  \frac{1}{3}e^t - \frac{1}{3}e^{-2t} </mrow>
							<mrow>  y(t)	 \amp =  \frac{1}{3}e^{-2t} + \frac{2}{3}e^t </mrow>

						</md>
						We can verify our solution.
						<md>
							<mrow>  \mbox{LHS of first DE}	 \amp =  \frac{dx}{dt} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{d}{dt}\left( \frac{1}{3}e^t - \frac{1}{3}e^{-2t} \right) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{3}e^{t} + \frac{2}{3}e^{-2t} </mrow>
							<mrow>  \mbox{RHS of first DE}	 \amp =  -x+y </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -\left( \frac{1}{3}e^t - \frac{1}{3}e^{-2t} \right) + \left( \frac{1}{3}e^{-2t} + \frac{2}{3}e^t \right) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{3}e^t + \frac{2}{3}e^{-2t} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \mbox{LHS of first DE} </mrow>
							<mrow>  \mbox{LHS of second DE}	 \amp =  \frac{dy}{dt} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{d}{dt}\left( \frac{1}{3}e^{-2t} + \frac{2}{3}e^t \right) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -\frac{2}{3}e^{-2t} + \frac{2}{3}e^t </mrow>
							<mrow>  \mbox{RHS of second DE}	 \amp =  2x </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  2\left( \frac{1}{3}e^t - \frac{1}{3}e^{-2t} \right) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{2}{3}e^t - \frac{2}{3}e^{-2t} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \mbox{LHS of second DE} </mrow>
							<mrow>  x(0)	 \amp =  \frac{1}{3}e^0 - \frac{1}{3}e^{-2\cdot 0} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{3}\cdot 1 - \frac{1}{3}\cdot 1 </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  0 </mrow>
							<mrow>  y(0)	 \amp =  \frac{1}{3}e^{-2\cdot 0} + \frac{2}{3}e^0 </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{3}\cdot 1 + \frac{2}{3}\cdot 1 </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  1 </mrow>

						</md>
						Hence, the solution satisfies both DEs and both initial conditions.
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<m>x(t) = \frac{1}{3}e^t - \frac{1}{3}e^{-2t},\quad y(t) = \frac{1}{3}e^{-2t} + \frac{2}{3}e^t </m>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
						<m>
							\left\{
							\begin{array}{rll}
								\dfrac{dx}{dt} =\amp x - 2y,\amp x(0)	= -1,\\
								\dfrac{dy}{dt} =\amp 5x - y,\amp y(0)	= 2.
							\end{array}
							\right.
						</m>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						We can take the LT of each DE, starting with the first DE.  We will then solve for<m>X(s). </m>
						<md>
							<mrow>  \frac{dx}{dt}	 \amp =  x-2y</mrow>
							<mrow>  \lap{\frac{dx}{dt}}	 \amp =  \lap{x-2y}</mrow>
							<mrow>  sX(s) - x(0)	 \amp =  \lap{x} - 2 \lap{y}</mrow>
							<mrow>  sX(s) + 1	 \amp =  X(s) - 2Y(s)</mrow>
							<mrow>  sX(s) - X(s)	 \amp =  -2Y(s) - 1</mrow>
							<mrow>  X(s)[s-1]	 \amp =  -2Y(s) - 1</mrow>
							<mrow>  X(s)	 \amp =  \frac{-2}{s-1}Y(s) - \frac{1}{s-1}</mrow>
						</md>
						Now we take the LT of the second DE.  We will substitute in for<m>X(s) </m> using the result we found above.
						<md>
							<mrow>  \frac{dy}{dt}	 \amp =  5x - y </mrow>
							<mrow>  \lap{\frac{dy}{dt}}	 \amp =  \lap{5x - y} </mrow>
							<mrow>  sY(s) - y(0)	 \amp =  5\lap{x} - \lap{y} </mrow>
							<mrow>  sY(s) - 2	 \amp =  5X(s) - Y(s) </mrow>
							<mrow>  sY(s) - 2	 \amp =  5\left[ \frac{-2}{s-1}Y(s) - \frac{1}{s-1} \right] - Y(s) </mrow>
							<mrow>  sY(s) - 2	 \amp =  \frac{-10}{s-1}Y(s) - \frac{5}{s-1}- Y(s) </mrow>
							<mrow>  (s-1) \cdot \left( sY(s) - 2 \right)	 \amp =  \left( \frac{-10}{s-1}Y(s) - \frac{5}{s-1}- Y(s) \right) \cdot (s-1) </mrow>
							<mrow>  (s^2 - s)Y(s) - 2s + 2	 \amp =  -10Y(s) - 5 - (s-1)Y(s) </mrow>
							<mrow>  (s^2 - s)Y(s) + 10Y(s) + (s-1)Y(s)	 \amp =  2s - 2 - 5 </mrow>
							<mrow>  Y(s)[s^2 - s + 10 + s - 1]	 \amp =  2s - 7 </mrow>
							<mrow>  Y(s)[s^2 + 9]	 \amp =  2s - 7 </mrow>
							<mrow>  Y(s)	 \amp =  \frac{2s - 7}{s^2 + 9} </mrow>

						</md>
						We now substitute this back into equation.
						<md>
							<mrow>  X(s)	 \amp =  \frac{-2}{s-1}Y(s) - \frac{1}{s-1} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{-2}{s-1}\cdot\frac{2s - 7}{s^2 + 9} - \frac{1}{s-1} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{-4s+14}{(s-1)(s^2 + 9)} - \frac{1}{s-1}\cdot \frac{s^2 + 9}{s^2 + 9} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{(-4s + 14) - (s^2 + 9) }{(s-1)(s^2 + 9)} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{-4s + 14 - s^2 - 9) }{(s-1)(s^2 + 9)} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{-s^2 - 4s + 5}{(s-1)(s^2 + 9)} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{-(s^2 + 4s - 5)}{(s-1)(s^2 + 9)} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{-(s+5)(s-1)}{(s-1)(s^2 + 9)} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{-(s+5)}{s^2 + 9} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{-s-5}{s^2 + 9} </mrow>

						</md>
						We need only take the inverse LT of each function in order to solve for the desired functions <m>x(t) </m> and <m>y(t). </m>
						<md>
							<mrow>  x(t)	 \amp =   \lap^{-1}\left\{ X(s) \right\} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{-s-5}{s^2 + 9} \right\}  </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  - \lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{s}{s^2 + 9} \right\} - 5 \lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{1}{s^2 + 9} \right\}  </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  - \cos(3t) - 5 \lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{1}{s^2 + 9} \right\}\cdot \frac{3}{3}  </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  - \cos(3t) - 5 \lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{3}{s^2 + 3^2} \right\}\cdot \frac{1}{3}  </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  - \cos(3t) - \frac{5}{3} \sin(3t)  </mrow>
						</md>
						
						<md>
							<mrow>  y(t)	 \amp =  \lap^{-1}\left\{ Y(s) \right\} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{2s - 7}{s^2 + 9} \right\} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  2\lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{s}{s^2 + 9} \right\} - 7\lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{1}{s^2 + 9} \right\} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  2\cos(3t) - 7\lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{1}{s^2 + 9} \right\}\cdot \frac{3}{3} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  2\cos(3t) - 7\lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{3}{s^2 + 3^2} \right\}\cdot \frac{1}{3} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  2\cos(3t) - \frac{7}{3}\sin(3t) </mrow>

						</md>
						Thus, the solution to this system is
						<md>
							<mrow>  x(t)	 \amp =  -\cos(3t) - \frac{5}{3} \sin(3t) </mrow>
							<mrow>  y(t)	 \amp =  2\cos(3t) - \frac{7}{3}\sin(3t) </mrow>

						</md>
						We can verify our solution.
						<md>
							<mrow>  \mbox{LHS of first DE}	 \amp =  \frac{dx}{dt} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{d}{dt}\left( -\cos(3t) - \frac{5}{3} \sin(3t) \right) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  3\sin(3t) - 5\cos(3t) </mrow>
							<mrow>  \mbox{RHS of first DE}	 \amp =  x-2y </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \left( -\cos(3t) - \frac{5}{3} \sin(3t) \right) -2 \left( 2\cos(3t) - \frac{7}{3}\sin(3t) \right) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -\cos(3t) - \frac{5}{3} \sin(3t) - 4\cos(3t) + \frac{14}{3}\sin(3t) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -5\cos(3t) + \frac{9}{3}\sin(3t) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -5\cos(3t) + 3\sin(3t)  </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \mbox{LHS of first DE} </mrow>
							<mrow>  \mbox{LHS of second DE}	 \amp =  \frac{dy}{dt} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{d}{dt}\left( 2\cos(3t) - \frac{7}{3}\sin(3t) \right) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -6\sin(3t) - 7\cos(3t) </mrow>
							<mrow>  \mbox{RHS of second DE}	 \amp =  5x - y </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  5\left( -\cos(3t) - \frac{5}{3} \sin(3t) \right) - \left( 2\cos(3t) - \frac{7}{3}\sin(3t) \right) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -5\cos(3t) - \frac{25}{3} \sin(3t) - 2\cos(3t) + \frac{7}{3}\sin(3t) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -7\cos(3t)- \frac{18}{3} \sin(3t) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -7\cos(3t) - 6\sin(3t) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \mbox{LHS of second DE} </mrow>
							<mrow>  x(0)	 \amp =  -\cos(3\cdot 0) - \frac{5}{3} \sin(3\cdot 0) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -1 - 0 </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -1 </mrow>
							<mrow>  y(0)	 \amp =  2\cos(3\cdot 0) - \frac{7}{3}\sin(3\cdot 0) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  2\cdot 1 - 0 </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  2  </mrow>
						</md>
						Hence, the solution satisfies both DEs and both initial conditions.
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<m>x(t) = -\cos(3t) - \frac{5}{3} \sin(3t),\quad y(t) = 2\cos(3t) - \frac{7}{3}\sin(3t) </m>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
						<m>
							\left\{
							\begin{array}{rll}
								y' - 2x = 1,						\amp x(0)	= 0,\\
								x' + y' - 3x - 3y = 2,	\amp y(0)	= 0.
							\end{array}
							\right.
						</m>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						We can take the LT of each DE, starting with the first DE.  We will then solve for<m>X(s). </m>
						<md>
							<mrow>  y' - 2x	 \amp =  1</mrow>
							<mrow>  \lap{ y' - 2x }	 \amp =  \lap{ 1 }</mrow>
							<mrow>  sY(s) -y(0) - 2X(s)	 \amp =  \frac{1}{s}</mrow>
							<mrow>  sY(s) - 0 - 2X(s)	 \amp =  \frac{1}{s}</mrow>
							<mrow>  sY(s)	 \amp =  \frac{1}{s}+ 2X(s)</mrow>
							<mrow>  Y(s)	 \amp =  \frac{1}{s^2} + \frac{2}{s}X(s)</mrow>
						</md>
						Now we take the LT of the second DE.  We will substitute in for<m>Y(s) </m> using the result we found above.
						<md>
							<mrow>  x' + y' - 3x - 3y	 \amp =  2 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \lap{ x' + y' - 3x - 3y }	 \amp =  \lap{2} </mrow>
							<mrow>  sX(s) - x(0) + sY(s) - y(0) - 3X(s) - 3Y(s)	 \amp =  \frac{2}{s} </mrow>
							<mrow>  sX(s) - 0 + sY(s) - 0 - 3X(s) - 3Y(s)	 \amp =  \frac{2}{s} </mrow>
							<mrow>  sX(s) - 3X(s) + (s-3) Y(s)	 \amp =  \frac{2}{s} </mrow>
							<mrow>  sX(s) - 3X(s) + (s-3)\left[ \frac{1}{s^2} + \frac{2}{s}X(s) \right]	 \amp =  \frac{2}{s} </mrow>
							<mrow>  sX(s) - 3X(s) + \frac{s-3}{s^2} + \frac{2(s-3)}{s}X(s)	 \amp =  \frac{2}{s} </mrow>
							<mrow>  sX(s) - 3X(s) + \frac{2(s-3)}{s}X(s)	 \amp =  \frac{2}{s} - \frac{s-3}{s^2}  </mrow>
							<mrow>  s^2 \cdot \left[sX(s) - 3X(s) + \frac{2(s-3)}{s}X(s)\right]	 \amp =  s^2\cdot \left[\frac{2}{s} - \frac{s-3}{s^2}\right]  </mrow>
							<mrow>  s^3X(s) - 3s^2X(s) + 2s(s-3)X(s)	 \amp =  2s - (s-3) </mrow>
							<mrow>  X(s) [s^3 - 3s^2 + (2s^2 - 6s)]	 \amp =  2s - s + 3 </mrow>
							<mrow>  X(s)	[s^3 - s^2  - 6s]	 \amp =  s+3 </mrow>
							<mrow>  X(s)	 \amp =  \frac{s+3}{s^3 - s^2  - 6s} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{s+3}{s(s^2 - s - 6)} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{s+3}{s(s-3)(s+2)}  </mrow>
						</md>
						We now substitute this back into equation.
						<md>
							<mrow>  Y(s)	 \amp =  \frac{1}{s^2} + \frac{2}{s}X(s) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{s^2} + \frac{2}{s}\cdot \frac{s+3}{s(s-3)(s+2)} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{s^2} + \frac{2(s+3)}{s^2(s-3)(s+2)} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{s^2}\cdot \frac{(s-3)(s+2)}{(s-3)(s+2)} + \frac{2(s+3)}{s^2(s-3)(s+2)} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{(s-3)(s+2) + 2(s+3)}{s^2(s-3)(s+2)} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{s^2 - s - 6 + 2s + 6}{s^2(s-3)(s+2)} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{s^2 + s}{s^2(s-3)(s+2)} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{s(s+1)}{s^2(s-3)(s+2)} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{s+1}{s(s-3)(s+2)}  </mrow>
						</md>
						We need only take the inverse LT of each function in order to solve for the desired function <m>x(t) </m> and <m>y(t). </m> This means we will need to find a partial fraction decomposition for each.
						<md>
							<mrow>  \frac{s+3}{s(s-3)(s+2)}	 \amp =  \frac{A}{s} + \frac{B}{s-3} + \frac{C}{s+2} </mrow>
							<mrow>  s+3	 \amp =  A(s-3)(s+2) + B(s)(s+2) + C(s)(s-3) </mrow>
							<mrow>  0s^2 + s + 3	 \amp =  A(s^2 - s - 6) + B(s^2 + 2s) + C(s^2 - 3s) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  As^2  - As - 6A + Bs^2 + 2Bs + Cs^2 - 3Cs </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  (A+B+C)s^2 + (-A + 2B- 3C)s + (-6A) </mrow>
						</md>
					
						<md>
							<mrow>  A+B+C	 \amp =  0					\amp 				-A + 2B - 3C	\amp = 1		\amp	-6A	\amp = 3 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp					\amp							\amp		\amp	A	 \amp =  -\frac{1}{2} </mrow>
							<mrow>  B + C	 \amp =  -A				\amp					2B - 3C	\amp = 1 + A	\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  B + C	 \amp =  -\left( -\frac{1}{2} \right)	\amp	2B - 3C	\amp = 1 + \left( -\frac{1}{2} \right)	\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  B + C	 \amp =  \frac{1}{2}			\amp 	2B - 3C	\amp = \frac{1}{2}				\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  C	 \amp =  \frac{1}{2} - B		\amp			\amp						\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp	\amp 2B - 3\left( \frac{1}{2} - B \right)	 \amp =  \frac{1}{2}				\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp			\amp 2B - \frac{3}{2} + 3B	 \amp =  \frac{1}{2}				\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp					\amp 		5B	 \amp =  \frac{1}{2} + \frac{3}{2}		\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp					\amp		5B	 \amp =  2						\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp					\amp		B	 \amp =  \frac{2}{5}				\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  C	 \amp =  \frac{1}{2} - B		\amp			\amp						\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{2} - \frac{2}{5}	\amp			\amp						\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{10}			\amp			\amp						\amp		\amp  </mrow>
						</md>
						Hence,
						<md>
							<mrow>   X(s)	 \amp =  \frac{-\frac{1}{2}}{s} + \frac{\frac{2}{5}}{s-3} + \frac{\frac{1}{10}}{s+2}</mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -\frac{1}{2}\cdot \frac{1}{s} + \frac{2}{5}\cdot \frac{1}{s-3} + \frac{1}{10}\cdot \frac{1}{s+2}</mrow>
						</md>
						Similarly, we will find a partial fraction decomposition for<m>Y(s). </m>
						<md>
							<mrow>  \frac{s+1}{s(s-3)(s+2)}	 \amp =  \frac{A}{s} + \frac{B}{s-3} + \frac{C}{s+2} </mrow>
							<mrow>  s+1	 \amp =  A(s-3)(s+2) + B(s)(s+2) + C(s)(s-3) </mrow>
							<mrow>  0s^2 + s + 1	 \amp =  A(s^2 - s - 6) + B(s^2 + 2s) + C(s^2 - 3s) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  As^2  - As - 6A + Bs^2 + 2Bs + Cs^2 - 3Cs </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  (A+B+C)s^2 + (-A + 2B- 3C)s + (-6A) </mrow>

						</md>
						
						<md>
							<mrow>  A+B+C	 \amp =  0					\amp 				-A + 2B - 3C	\amp = 1		\amp	-6A	\amp = 1 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp					\amp							\amp		\amp	A	 \amp =  -\frac{1}{6} </mrow>
							<mrow>  B + C	 \amp =  -A				\amp					2B - 3C	\amp = 1 + A	\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  B + C	 \amp =  -\left( -\frac{1}{6} \right)	\amp	2B - 3C	\amp = 1 + \left( -\frac{1}{6} \right)	\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  B + C	 \amp =  \frac{1}{6}			\amp 	2B - 3C	\amp = \frac{5}{6}				\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  C	 \amp =  \frac{1}{6} - B		\amp			\amp						\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp	\amp 2B - 3\left( \frac{1}{6} - B \right)	 \amp =  \frac{5}{6}				\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp			\amp 2B - \frac{1}{2} + 3B	 \amp =  \frac{5}{6}				\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp					\amp 		5B	 \amp =  \frac{5}{6} + \frac{1}{2}		\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp					\amp		5B	 \amp =  \frac{4}{3}				\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp					\amp		B	 \amp =  \frac{4}{15}				\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>  C	 \amp =  \frac{1}{6} - B		\amp			\amp						\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{1}{6} - \frac{4}{15}\amp			\amp						\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{5}{30} - \frac{8}{30}\amp			\amp						\amp		\amp </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -\frac{1}{10}			\amp			\amp						\amp		\amp  </mrow>
						</md>
						Hence,
						<md>
							<mrow>   Y(s)	 \amp =  \frac{-\frac{1}{6}}{s} + \frac{\frac{4}{15}}{s-3} + \frac{-\frac{1}{10}}{s+2}</mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -\frac{1}{6}\cdot \frac{1}{s} + \frac{4}{15}\cdot \frac{1}{s-3} - \frac{1}{10}\cdot \frac{1}{s+2}</mrow>
						</md>
						Now we need only find the inverse LT of equations.
						<md>
							<mrow>  x(t)	 \amp =   \lap^{-1}\left\{ X(s) \right\} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \lap^{-1}\left\{ -\frac{1}{2}\cdot \frac{1}{s} + \frac{2}{5}\cdot \frac{1}{s-3} + \frac{1}{10}\cdot \frac{1}{s+2} \right\} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -\frac{1}{2}\lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{1}{s} \right\} + \frac{2}{5} \lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{1}{s-3} \right\} + \frac{1}{10}\lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{1}{s+2} \right\} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -\frac{1}{2} + \frac{2}{5}e^{3t} + \frac{1}{10}e^{-2t} </mrow>
							<mrow>  y(t)	 \amp =  \lap^{-1}\left\{ Y(s) \right\} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \lap^{-1}\left\{ -\frac{1}{6}\cdot \frac{1}{s} + \frac{4}{15}\cdot \frac{1}{s-3} - \frac{1}{10}\cdot \frac{1}{s+2} \right\} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -\frac{1}{6}\lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{1}{s} \right\} + \frac{4}{15}\lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{1}{s-3} \right\} - \frac{1}{10} \lap^{-1}\left\{ \frac{1}{s+2} \right\} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -\frac{1}{6}+ \frac{4}{15}e^{3t} - \frac{1}{10} e^{-2t} </mrow>

						</md>
						Thus, the solution to this system is
						<md>
							<mrow>  x(t)	 \amp =  -\frac{1}{2} + \frac{2}{5}e^{3t} + \frac{1}{10}e^{-2t} </mrow>
							<mrow>  y(t)	 \amp =  -\frac{1}{6}+ \frac{4}{15}e^{3t} - \frac{1}{10} e^{-2t} </mrow>

						</md>
						We can verify that this is the solution.
						<md>
							<mrow>  \mbox{LHS of first DE}	 \amp =  y' - 2x </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{d}{dt}\left( -\frac{1}{6}+ \frac{4}{15}e^{3t} - \frac{1}{10} e^{-2t} \right) - 2\Big( -\frac{1}{2} + \frac{2}{5}e^{3t} + \frac{1}{10}e^{-2t} \Big) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \left( 0 + \frac{4}{5}e^{3t} + \frac{1}{5} e^{-2t} \right) + 1 - \frac{4}{5}e^{3t} - \frac{1}{5}e^{-2t} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  1 </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \mbox{RHS of first DE} </mrow>
							<mrow>  \mbox{RHS of second DE}	 \amp =  x' + y' - 3x - 3y </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \frac{d}{dt}\left( -\frac{1}{2} + \frac{2}{5}e^{3t} + \frac{1}{10}e^{-2t} \right) + \frac{d}{dt}\left( -\frac{1}{6}+ \frac{4}{15}e^{3t} - \frac{1}{10} e^{-2t} \right) </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \mbox{}\hspace{1cm} - 3 \left( -\frac{1}{2} + \frac{2}{5}e^{3t} + \frac{1}{10}e^{-2t} \right) - 3 \left( -\frac{1}{6}+ \frac{4}{15}e^{3t} - \frac{1}{10} e^{-2t} \right) </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp =  \left(0 + \frac{6}{5}e^{3t} - \frac{1}{5}e^{-2t} \right) + \left( 0 + \frac{4}{5}e^{3t} + \frac{1}{5} e^{-2t} \right) </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \mbox{}\hspace{1cm} + \frac{3}{2} - \frac{6}{5}e^{3t} - \frac{3}{10}e^{-2t} + \frac{1}{2} - \frac{4}{5}e^{3t} + \frac{3}{10} e^{-2t} </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp =  \left( \frac{6}{5} + \frac{4}{5} - \frac{6}{5} - \frac{4}{5} \right)e^{3t} + \left( - \frac{1}{5} + \frac{1}{5} - \frac{3}{10} + \frac{3}{10} \right)e^{-2t} + \left( \frac{3}{2} + \frac{1}{2} \right) </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  0 + 0 + 2 </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  2 </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \mbox{RHS of second DE} </mrow>
							<mrow>  x(0)	 \amp =  -\frac{1}{2} + \frac{2}{5}e^{3\cdot 0} + \frac{1}{10}e^{-2\cdot 0} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -\frac{1}{2} + \frac{2}{5} + \frac{1}{10} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -\frac{5}{10} + \frac{4}{10} + \frac{1}{10} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  0 </mrow>
							<mrow>  y(0)	 \amp =  -\frac{1}{6} + \frac{4}{15}e^{3\cdot 0} - \frac{1}{10} e^{-2\cdot 0} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -\frac{1}{6} + \frac{4}{15} - \frac{1}{10} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  -\frac{5}{30} + \frac{8}{30} - \frac{3}{30} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  0  </mrow>
						</md>
						Hence, the solution satisfies both DEs and both initial conditions.
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<m>x(t) = -\frac{1}{2} + \frac{2}{5}e^{3t} + \frac{1}{10}e^{-2t},\quad y(t) = -\frac{1}{6}+ \frac{4}{15}e^{3t} - \frac{1}{10} e^{-2t} </m>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

		</exercisegroup>

		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Suppose a mixture containing 0.3 kg of sugar per liter runs into a tank initially filled with 400 L of water containing 2 kg of sugar.  The liquid enters at 10 L/min,the mixture is kept uniform by stirring, and the mixture flows out at the same rate.
				</p>

				<p>
					Answer the following:
					<ol marker="(a)">
						<li>Find the mass of sugar in the tank after <m>t </m> minutes.</li>
						<li>Find the concentration of sugar in the tank after 10 minutes.</li>
						<li>Use your answer to question to determine the <alert>concentration</alert> of sugar in the tank after a long time. Does your answer make sense in terms of the physical scenario? Explain.</li>
					</ol>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) Let <m>S(t)</m> be the mass of sugar (kg) in the tank. The volume stays at 400 L since inflow and outflow rates match. Then
					<md>
						<mrow> \frac{dS}{dt} \amp = \underbrace{(0.3)(10)}_{\text{rate in}} - \underbrace{\frac{S}{400}(10)}_{\text{rate out}} = 3 - \frac{S}{40} </mrow>
					</md>
					with <m>S(0) = 2</m>. This first-order linear (and separable) equation has equilibrium <m>S = 120</m>, so
					<md>
						S(t) = 120 - 118e^{-t/40}.
					</md>
					(Check: <m>S(0) = 120 - 118 = 2</m> ✓.)
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) <m>S(10) = 120 - 118e^{-1/4} \approx 28.10</m> kg, so the concentration is <m>\dfrac{S(10)}{400} \approx 0.070</m> kg/L.
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) As <m>t \to \infty</m>, <m>S \to 120</m> kg, so the concentration approaches <m>\dfrac{120}{400} = 0.3</m> kg/L — exactly the concentration of the incoming mixture. This makes sense: after a long time the original contents have essentially washed out, and the tank matches what is being pumped in.
				</p>
			</solution>
			<answer>
				<p>
					(a) <m>S(t) = 120 - 118e^{-t/40}</m> kg; (b) <m>\approx 0.070</m> kg/L; (c) <m>0.3</m> kg/L, the inflow concentration.
				</p>
			</answer>
		</exercise>

		<exercise>
			<statement>
				A brine solution of salt flows at a constant rate of 4 L/min into a large tank that initially holds 100 L of pure water.  The solution inside the tank is kept well-stirred and flows out of the tank at a rate of 3 L/min. Suppose the concentration of salt in the brine entering the tank is <m>0.2</m> kg/L. Then
				<p>
				<ol marker="(a)">
					<li>Determine the mass of the salt in the tank after <m>t </m> minutes.</li>
					<li>What is the concentration of salt after one hour?</li>
				</ol>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) Let <m>S(t)</m> be the mass of salt (kg). The volume is <em>not</em> constant here: 4 L/min enters but only 3 L/min leaves, so <m>V(t) = 100 + t</m>. Then
					<md>
						<mrow> \frac{dS}{dt} \amp = \underbrace{(0.2)(4)}_{\text{rate in}} - \underbrace{\frac{S}{100+t}(3)}_{\text{rate out}} = 0.8 - \frac{3S}{100+t} </mrow>
					</md>
					with <m>S(0) = 0</m>. In standard form, <m>S' + \frac{3}{100+t}S = 0.8</m>, with integrating factor
					<md>
						\mu(t) = e^{\int \frac{3}{100+t}\,dt} = (100+t)^3.
					</md>
					Then
					<md>
						<mrow> \left[(100+t)^3 S\right]' \amp = 0.8(100+t)^3 </mrow>
						<mrow> (100+t)^3 S \amp = 0.2(100+t)^4 + c </mrow>
						<mrow> S(t) \amp = 0.2(100+t) + \frac{c}{(100+t)^3} </mrow>
					</md>
					and <m>S(0) = 0</m> gives <m>c = -0.2(100)^4 = -2\times 10^7</m>. Hence
					<md>
						S(t) = 0.2(100+t) - \frac{2\times 10^7}{(100+t)^3}.
					</md>
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) After one hour, <m>t = 60</m> and <m>V = 160</m> L:
					<md>
						S(60) = 0.2(160) - \frac{2\times 10^7}{160^3} \approx 32 - 4.88 = 27.12 \text{ kg}
					</md>
					so the concentration is <m>\dfrac{S(60)}{160} \approx 0.17</m> kg/L.
				</p>
			</solution>
			<answer>
				<p>
					(a) <m>\ds S(t) = 0.2(100+t) - \frac{2\times 10^7}{(100+t)^3}</m> kg; (b) <m>\approx 0.17</m> kg/L.
				</p>
			</answer>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ex-second-order-to-system">
			<title>From a Second-Order Equation to a System</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Rewrite the second-order equation
					<md>
						y'' - y = 0
					</md>
					as a system of first-order equations.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Let <m>u = y</m> and <m>v = y'</m>. Then:
				</p>

				<md>
					u' = v
				</md>
				<p>
					and
				</p>
				<md>
					v' = y'' = y = u
				</md>

				<p>
					So the system becomes:
				</p>

				<md>
					<mrow> u' \amp = v </mrow>
					<mrow> v' \amp = u </mrow>
				</md>
			</solution>
			<answer>
				<p>
					<m>u' = v, \quad v' = u</m>
				</p>
			</answer>
		</exercise>

		<exercisegroup>

			<introduction>
				<p>
					Two large tanks, each holding 100 L of liquid, are interconnected by pipes, with the liquid flowing from tank 1 into tank 2 at 3 L/min and from tank 2 into tank 1 at 1 L/min. The liquid in each tank is kept well stirred. A brine solution with a salt concentration of 0.01 kg/L flows into tank 1 at a rate of 4 L/min.  The (diluted) solution flows out of the system from tank 1 at 2 L/min and from tank 2 at 2 L/min.Initially, tank 1 contains pure water and tank 2 contains 6 kg of salt.
				</p>
			</introduction>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Write a system of differential equations for<m>x_1(t) </m> (the amount of salt, in kg, in tank 1 at time <m>t </m> )and <m>x_2(t) </m> (the amount of salt, in kg, in tank 2 at time <m>t </m> ).
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						We consider the rate of change in the amount of salt in tank 1.
						<md>
							<mrow>  \frac{dx_1}{dt}  \amp =  \mbox{(rate of salt into the tank)} - \mbox{(rate of salt out of the tank)} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \Bigg[\underbrace{0.1 \cdot 4}_{ \frac{\mbox{kg}}{\mbox{L}}\cdot\frac{\mbox{L}}{\mbox{min}}} + \underbrace{\frac{x_2}{100}\cdot 1}_{ \frac{\mbox{kg}}{\mbox{L}}\cdot\frac{\mbox{L}}{\mbox{min}}}\Bigg] - \Bigg[\underbrace{\frac{x_1}{100}\cdot 3}_{ \frac{\mbox{kg}}{\mbox{L}}\cdot\frac{\mbox{L}}{\mbox{min}}}\Bigg] </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp = 0.4 + \frac{1}{100}x_2 - \frac{1}{20}x_1  </mrow>
						</md>
						Similarly, we consider the rate of change in the amount of salt in tank 2.
						<md>
							<mrow>  \frac{dx_2}{dt}  \amp =  \mbox{(rate of salt into the tank)} - \mbox{(rate of salt out of the tank)} </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp =  \Bigg[\underbrace{\frac{x_1}{100}\cdot 3}_{ \frac{\mbox{kg}}{\mbox{L}}\cdot\frac{\mbox{L}}{\mbox{min}}}\Bigg] - \Bigg[\underbrace{\frac{x_2}{100}\cdot 3}_{ \frac{\mbox{kg}}{\mbox{L}}\cdot\frac{\mbox{L}}{\mbox{min}}}\Bigg] </mrow>
							<mrow>   \amp = \frac{3}{100}x_1 - \frac{3}{100}x_2  </mrow>
						</md>
						Hence, our system is:
						<md>
							<mrow>  x'_1	 \amp = - \frac{1}{20}x_1+ \frac{1}{100}x_2 + 0.4, </mrow>
							<mrow>  x'_2	 \amp =  \frac{3}{100}x_1 - \frac{3}{100}x_2.  </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<m>x'_1 =- \frac{1}{20}x_1+ \frac{1}{100}x_2 + 0.4,x'_2 = \frac{3}{100}x_1 - \frac{3}{100}x_2 </m>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						How many initial conditions will you need to find a particular solution? Write the initial conditions.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						There are two first-order DEs, so we will need two initial conditions. They are: <m>x_1(0) = 0,\hspace{2cm} x_2(0) = 6. </m>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						two <m>x_1(0) = 0 </m> and <m>x_2(0) = 6 </m>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Why can't we solve each of the DEs you found individually using techniques we already know?
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						We can't solve this system using techniques we already know because <m>x_1(t) </m> and <m>x_2(t) </m> are both unknown functions, and each DE contains BOTH of the unknowns.  All of the techniques we have so far help us solve for a single unknown function.
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<m>x_1(t) </m> and <m>x_2(t) </m> are both unknown functions, and each DE contains BOTH of the unknowns
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

		</exercisegroup>

		<exercise>
			<statement>
				A simplified mathematical model for an arms race between two countries whose expenditures for	defense are expressed by the variables <m>x(t)</m> and <m>y(t)</m> is given by the linear system
				<md>
					<mrow>  \frac{dx}{dt}	 \amp =  2y - x + a		\amp x(0) = 1</mrow>
					<mrow>  \frac{dy}{dt}	 \amp =  4x - 3y + b	\amp y(0) = 4</mrow>
				</md>
				where <m>a </m> and <m>b </m> are constants that measure the trust (or distrust!) each country has for the other.
				<p>
				<ol marker="(a)">
					<li>What might be appropriate units for <m>x(t) </m> and <m>y(t)</m>?</li>
					<li>
						How can we interpret the fact that the coefficient of <m>y </m> is positive in the equation for <m>\frac{dx}{dt}</m>?
						Does it make sense? Would the DE make sense if the coefficient were negative instead?
					</li>
					<li>
						How can we interpret the fact that the coefficient of <m>y </m> is negative in the equation for <m>\frac{dy}{dt}</m>?
						Does it make sense? Would the DE make sense if the coefficient were positive instead?
					</li>
					<li>
						Suppose country X trusts country Y, but country Y doesn't trust country X.
						What can we say about <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>?
						Should they be positive, negative, or zero?</li>
					<li>
						Rewrite the system of differential equations in matrix form by using the vector
						<m>\vec{X} = \begin{bmatrix} x\\y \end{bmatrix}.</m>
						Notice that for this system, the right hand side should be of the form <m>A\vec{X} + \vec{B}.</m>
					</li>
					<li>
						Write the initial conditions as a vector as well. That is, complete the following.
						<m>\vec{X}(0) = \begin{bmatrix} ?\\? \end{bmatrix}</m>
					</li>
				</ol>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) Since <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are defense expenditures over time, natural units are currency per year (say, billions of dollars per year), with <m>t</m> in years.
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) The positive coefficient on <m>y</m> means country X <em>increases</em> its spending in response to country Y's spending — an escalation driven by distrust, which is the essence of an arms race. A negative coefficient would model a country that responds to a rival's buildup by <em>reducing</em> its own spending (appeasement or forced disarmament) — possible, but it describes a different political situation.
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) The negative coefficient on <m>y</m> in its own equation is self-restraint: the larger Y's current budget, the harder it is to grow it further (economic burden). A positive coefficient would mean Y's spending feeds on itself, growing without any brake — a runaway model that is harder to justify.
				</p>
				<p>
					(d) The constants shift each country's baseline spending. If X trusts Y, then <m>a \lt 0</m> (X reduces spending independent of Y's behavior); if Y distrusts X, then <m>b \gt 0</m>.
				</p>
				<p>
					(e) <m>\ds \frac{d\vec{X}}{dt} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 2 \\ 4 \amp -3 \end{bmatrix}\vec{X} + \begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \end{bmatrix}</m>
				</p>
				<p>
					(f) <m>\ds \vec{X}(0) = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</m>
				</p>
			</solution>
			<answer>
				<p>
					(e) <m>\ds \frac{d\vec{X}}{dt} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 2 \\ 4 \amp -3 \end{bmatrix}\vec{X} + \begin{bmatrix} a \\ b \end{bmatrix}</m>; (f) <m>\ds \vec{X}(0) = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</m>
				</p>
			</answer>
		</exercise>

		<exercisegroup>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Suppose compartments A and B are filled with fluids and are separated by a permeable membrane. The figure is a compartmental representation of the exterior and interior of a cell.  Suppose, too, that a nutrient necessary for cell growth passes through the membrane.
						<figure xml:id="concentration-membrane">
							<caption>A two-compartment model of a cell: compartments <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> separated by a permeable membrane through which the nutrient passes.</caption>
							<image width="50%" source="./figures/concentration.png">
								<shortdescription>A two-compartment diagram of a cell's interior and exterior separated by a permeable membrane, through which a nutrient passes between the two compartments.</shortdescription>
							</image>
						</figure>
						A model for the amounts <m>x(t)</m> and <m>y(t)</m> of the nutrient in compartments A and B, respectively, at time <m>t</m> is given by the linear system of differential equations:
						<md>
							<mrow>\frac{dx}{dt}	=\amp \kappa\left(\frac{y}{V_B}-\frac{x}{V_A}\right), </mrow>
							<mrow>\frac{dy}{dt}	=\amp \kappa\left(\frac{x}{V_A}-\frac{y}{V_B}\right). </mrow>
						</md>
						where <m>V_A</m> and <m>V_B</m> are the volumes of the compartments (so <m>\sfrac{x}{V_A}</m> and <m>\sfrac{y}{V_B}</m> are the concentrations), and <m>\kappa &gt; 0 </m> is a	permeability factor.
						Let <m>x(0) = x_0</m> and <m>y(0) = y_0</m>.
						<ol>
							<li>
								In the first equation, explain why it makes sense for <m>y</m> to have a positive coefficient
								and <m>x </m> to have a negative coefficient.
							</li>
							<li>
								Notice that if we add these two equations, we get
								<m>\frac{dx}{dt} + \frac{dy}{dt} = 0, </m>
								or, equivalently,
								<m>\frac{d}{dt}[x+y] = 0.</m> 
								Explain what this means and why it makes sense.
							</li>
							<li>
								Rewrite the system of differential equations in matrix form by using the vector
								<m>\vec{X} = \begin{bmatrix} x\\y \end{bmatrix}.</m>
							</li>
							<li>
								Write the initial conditions as a vector as well. That is, complete the following.
								<m>\vec{X}(0) = \begin{bmatrix} ?\\? \end{bmatrix}</m>
							</li>
						</ol>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						(a) The nutrient diffuses across the membrane from higher concentration to lower concentration. The concentration in B is <m>\sfrac{y}{V_B}</m>, and the higher it is, the faster nutrient flows <em>into</em> A — so <m>y</m> appears with a positive coefficient. The concentration in A, <m>\sfrac{x}{V_A}</m>, pushes nutrient <em>out</em> of A, so <m>x</m> appears with a negative coefficient.
					</p>
					<p>
						(b) <m>\frac{d}{dt}[x+y] = 0</m> says the total amount of nutrient <m>x + y</m> never changes — the membrane only moves nutrient between the compartments; none is created or destroyed. So <m>x(t) + y(t) = x_0 + y_0</m> for all time.
					</p>
					<p>
						(c) <m>\ds \frac{d\vec{X}}{dt} = \kappa\begin{bmatrix} -\sfrac{1}{V_A} \amp \sfrac{1}{V_B} \\ \sfrac{1}{V_A} \amp -\sfrac{1}{V_B} \end{bmatrix}\vec{X}</m>
					</p>
					<p>
						(d) <m>\ds \vec{X}(0) = \begin{bmatrix} x_0 \\ y_0 \end{bmatrix}</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						(c) <m>\ds \frac{d\vec{X}}{dt} = \kappa\begin{bmatrix} -\sfrac{1}{V_A} \amp \sfrac{1}{V_B} \\ \sfrac{1}{V_A} \amp -\sfrac{1}{V_B} \end{bmatrix}\vec{X}</m>; (d) <m>\ds \vec{X}(0) = \begin{bmatrix} x_0 \\ y_0 \end{bmatrix}</m>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					A tank contains 100 liters of water. Salt is being added at a rate of 5 grams per minute. If the mixture is kept uniform by stirring and salt is being removed from the tank at a rate of 2 liters per minute, set up the differential equation that models the amount of salt \(y(t)\) in the tank at any time \(t\).
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						Let \(y(t)\) be the amount of salt in the tank at time \(t\). The rate of change of salt with respect to time, \(\frac{dy}{dt}\), is given by the rate of salt coming in minus the rate of salt going out. The rate of salt coming in is 5 grams/minute. The concentration of salt in the tank is \(\frac{y(t)}{100 - 2t}\) and thus the rate at which salt is removed from the tank is \(2 \times \frac{y(t)}{100 - 2t}\). Therefore, the differential equation is:
						<md>
							\frac{dy}{dt} \amp = 5 - 2 \frac{y(t)}{100 - 2t}
						</md>
					</p>
				</solution>
			<answer>
				<md>
					\frac{dy}{dt} \amp = 5 - 2 \frac{y(t)}{100 - 2t}
				</md>
			</answer>
			</exercise>

		</exercisegroup>

		<exercise>
				<title>Euler's Method for Systems</title>

				<statement>
					<p>
						Given the initial-valued system
						<md>
							<mrow> y'	 \amp =  3z,\quad 	\amp y(2)	\amp = 3, </mrow>
							<mrow> z'	 \amp =  y+z^2,			\amp z(2)	\amp = -4 </mrow>
						</md>
						approximate <m>y(2.2)</m> and <m>z(2.2)</m> using two iterations of Euler's method with a step size <m>h = 0.1</m>.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						With <m>f_1(t,y,z) = 3z</m> and <m>f_2(t,y,z) = y + z^2</m>:
						<md>
							<mrow> \mbox{Iteration 1: } \amp \amp y_1 \amp = 3 + 0.1\cdot 3(-4) = 1.8 </mrow>
							<mrow> \amp \amp z_1 \amp = -4 + 0.1\cdot\big(3 + (-4)^2\big) = -2.1 </mrow>
							<mrow> \mbox{Iteration 2: } \amp \amp y_2 \amp = 1.8 + 0.1\cdot 3(-2.1) = 1.17 </mrow>
							<mrow> \amp \amp z_2 \amp = -2.1 + 0.1\cdot\big(1.8 + (-2.1)^2\big) = -1.479 </mrow>
						</md>
						Therefore <m>y(2.2) \approx 1.17</m> and <m>z(2.2) \approx -1.479</m>.
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p><m>y(2.2) \approx 1.17</m>, <m>z(2.2) \approx -1.479</m></p>
				</answer>
		</exercise>

		<exercise>
				<title>Euler's Method for Systems</title>

				<statement>
						<p>
								Consider the initial-valued system
								<md>
										<mrow> x'	\amp =  2x - y + t,	\amp x(0) = 6, </mrow>
										<mrow> y'	\amp =  x,					\amp y(0) = 2. </mrow>
								</md>
								Approximate <m>x(0.2) </m> and <m>y(0.2) </m> using <m>h = 0.1</m>.
						</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow>  \mbox{Preliminaries:	}	\amp \amp	f_1(t,x,y)	 \amp =  2x - y + t </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp	f_2(t,x,y)	 \amp =  x </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp	h	 \amp =  0.1 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp	t_0	 \amp =  0 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp	x_0	 \amp =  6 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp	y_0	 \amp =  2 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp \mbox{Iteration 1:}		\amp \amp	t_1	 \amp =  t_0 + h </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  0 + 0.1 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  0.1 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp	x_1	 \amp =  x_0 + h \cdot f_1(t_0,x_0,y_0) </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  6 + 0.1 \cdot f_1(0,6,2) </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  6 + 0.1 \cdot [2(6) - 2 + 0] </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  7 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp	y_1	 \amp =  y_0 + h\cdot f_2(t_0,x_0,y_0) </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  2 + 0.1 \cdot f_2(0,6,2) </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  2 + 0.1 \cdot [6] </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  2.6 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp \mbox{Iteration 2:}		\amp \amp	t_2	 \amp =  t_1 + h </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  0.1 + 0.1 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  0.2 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp	x_2	 \amp =  x_1 + h \cdot f_1(t_1,x_1,y_1) </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  7 + 0.1 \cdot f_1(0.1,7,2.6) </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  7 + 0.1 \cdot [2(7) - 2.6 + 0.1] </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  8.15 </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp	y_2	 \amp =  y_1 + h\cdot f_2(t_1,x_1,y_1) </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  2.6 + 0.1 \cdot f_2(0.1,7,2.6) </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  2.6 + 0.1 \cdot [7] </mrow>
							<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  3.3  </mrow>
						</md>
						Therefore <m>x(0.2) \approx 8.15 </m> and <m>y(0.2) \approx 3.3. </m>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<m>x(0.2) \approx 8.15 </m> <m> \hspace{0.5cm}y(0.2) \approx 3.3. </m>
					</p>
				</answer>
		</exercise>

		<exercisegroup cols="2">
			<title>Reduction of Order</title>

			<introduction>
				<p>
					Reduce each of the following to a system of first-order differential equations.
				</p>
			</introduction>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<m>y'' - 4y' + 4y = 0 </m>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						Let <m>u = y</m> and <m>v = y'</m>. Then <m>u' = v</m>, and substituting into the equation gives <m>v' - 4v + 4u = 0</m>, so:
						<md>
							<mrow> u' \amp = v </mrow>
							<mrow> v' \amp = 4v - 4u </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p><m>u' = v,\quad v' = 4v - 4u</m> where <m>u = y</m> and <m>v = y'</m></p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<m>x^2 y''' = 2y' </m>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						This is third-order, so we need three variables. Let <m>u = y</m>, <m>v = y'</m>, and <m>w = y''</m>. Then <m>u' = v</m>, <m>v' = w</m>, and substituting into the equation gives <m>x^2 w' = 2v</m>, so:
						<md>
							<mrow> u' \amp = v </mrow>
							<mrow> v' \amp = w </mrow>
							<mrow> w' \amp = \frac{2v}{x^2} </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p><m>u' = v,\quad v' = w,\quad w' = \dfrac{2v}{x^2}</m> where <m>u = y</m>, <m>v = y'</m>, and <m>w = y''</m></p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<m>y'' + x = 12,\quad x' + 2yt = \cos t </m>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
						We have one second-order and one first-order DE, which means we will need three variables to generate a system of three first-order DEs. Let <m>u = y,</m> <m>v = y',</m> and <m>w = x</m>.  Then we have the following.
						<md>
							<mrow> u'	 \amp =  y' = v \label{eq14-9}  </mrow>
						</md>
						Substituting into the first DE yields the following.
						<md>
							<mrow>  y'' + x	 \amp =  12 \nonumber </mrow>
							<mrow>  v' + w	 \amp =  12 \nonumber </mrow>
							<mrow>  v'	 \amp =  12 - w \label{eq14-10}  </mrow>
						</md>
						Substituting into the second DE yields the following.
						<md>
							<mrow>  w' + 2ut	 \amp =  \cos t \nonumber </mrow>
							<mrow>  w'	 \amp =  \cos t - 2ut \label{eq14-11}  </mrow>
						</md>
						Then equations (\ref{eq14-9}), (\ref{eq14-10}) and (\ref{eq14-11}) constitute a system of first-order DEs in the variable <m>u </m> <m>v </m> , and <m>w </m> , as below:
						<md>
							<mrow>  u'	 \amp =  v </mrow>
							<mrow>  v'	 \amp =  12 - w </mrow>
							<mrow>  w'	 \amp =  \cos t - 2ut  </mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<m>u' = v,v' = 12 - w,w' = \cos t - 2ut </m> where <m>u = y,v = y', </m> and <m>w = x </m>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>
		</exercisegroup>

		<exercise>
			<title>Euler's Method for Higher Order Systems</title>
			
			<statement>
				<p>
					Use Euler's method to approximate <m>y(0.2)</m> for the solution to the IVP
					<md>
						y'' + 2y' + y^2 = 0,\quad y(0) = 1,\quad y'(0) = 2
					</md>
					using a step size of <m>h = 0.1</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					First, we convert the second-order DE to a system of two first-order DEs. Let <m>u = y </m> and <m>v = y' </m>. Then
					<md xml:id="uprime-is-yprime">
						u' = y' = v
					</md>
					and 
					<md xml:id="vprime-is-yprimeprime">
						v' = (y')' = y''.
					</md>
					Substituting equations <xref ref="uprime-is-yprime"/> and <xref ref="vprime-is-yprimeprime"/> into the DE yields the following:
					<md>
						<mrow>  y'' + 2y' + y^2	 \amp =  0  </mrow>
						<mrow>  v' + 2v + u^2	 \amp =  0  </mrow>
						<mrow xml:id="yprimeprime-de">
							v'	 \amp =  -2v - u^2
						</mrow>
					</md>
					Then equations <xref ref="uprime-is-yprime"/> and <xref ref="yprimeprime-de"/> constitute a system of first-order DEs in the variable <m>u</m> and <m>v</m>.
					<md>
						<mrow>  u'	 \amp =  v </mrow>
						<mrow>  v'	 \amp =  -2v - u^2 </mrow>
					</md>
					Note that we can also convert the initial conditions to the new variables:
					<md>
						<mrow> u(0)	 \amp =  1 </mrow>
						<mrow> v(0)	 \amp =  2  </mrow>
					</md>
					Now we can use Euler's method as follows.
					<md>
						<mrow>  \mbox{Preliminaries:	}	\amp \amp	f_1(t,u,v)	 \amp =  v </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	f_2(t,u,v)	 \amp =  -2v-u^2 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	h	 \amp =  0.1 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	t_0	 \amp =  0 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	u_0	 \amp =  1 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	v_0	 \amp =  2 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp \mbox{Iteration 1:}		\amp \amp	t_1	 \amp =  t_0 + h </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  0 + 0.1 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  0.1 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	u_1	 \amp =  u_0 + h \cdot f_1(t_0,u_0,v_0) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  1 + 0.1 \cdot f_1(0,1,2) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  1 + 0.1 \cdot [2] </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  1.2 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	v_1	 \amp =  v_0 + h\cdot f_2(t_0,u_0,v_0) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  2 + 0.1 \cdot f_2(0,1,2) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  2 + 0.1 \cdot [-2(2) - (1)^2] </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  1.5 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp \mbox{Iteration 2:}		\amp \amp	t_2	 \amp =  t_1 + h </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  0.1 + 0.1 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  0.2 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	u_2	 \amp =  u_1 + h \cdot f_1(t_1,u_1,v_1) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  1.2 + 0.1 \cdot f_1(0.1, 1.2, 1.5) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  1.2 + 0.1 \cdot [1.5] </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  1.35 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	v_2	 \amp =  v_1 + h\cdot f_2(t_1,u_1,v_1) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  1.5 + 0.1 \cdot f_2(0.1, 1.2, 1.5) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  1.5 + 0.1 \cdot [-2(1.5) - (1.2)^2] </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  1.0560  </mrow>
					</md>
					Therefore <m>u(0.2) \approx 1.35 </m> and <m>v(0.2) \approx 1.0560. </m>	This means <m>y(0.2) \approx 1.35 </m> (and, even though we were not asked for it specifically, <m>y'(0.2) \approx 1.0560 </m>).
				</p>
			</solution>
			<answer><p><m>y(0.2) \approx 1.35 </m></p></answer>
		</exercise>

		<exercise>
			<title>Euler's Method</title>

			<statement>
				<p>
					Approximate the solution to the IVP
					<md>
						y'' - 2y = e^{t-3}\cos t,\quad y(3) = -1,\quad y'(3) = 0
					</md>
					at <m>t = 3.2</m> using one iteration of Euler's Method with <m>h = 0.2</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					First, we convert the second-order DE to a system of two first-order DEs. Let <m>u = y </m> and <m>v = y' </m>. Then
					<md xml:id="uprime-is-yprime2">
						u' = y' = v
					</md>
					and 
					<md xml:id="vprime-is-yprimeprime2">
						v' = (y')' = y''.
					</md>
					Substituting equations <xref ref="uprime-is-yprime2"/> and <xref ref="vprime-is-yprimeprime2"/> into the DE yields the following:
					<md>
						<mrow>  y'' - 2y	 \amp =  e^{t-3} \cos t  </mrow>
						<mrow>  v' - 2u	 \amp =  e^{t-3}\cos t </mrow>
						<mrow xml:id="yprimeprime-de2">
							v'	 \amp =  e^{t-3}\cos t + 2u
						</mrow>
					</md>
					Then equations <xref ref="uprime-is-yprime2"/> and <xref ref="yprimeprime-de2"/> constitute a system of first-order DEs in the variable <m>u</m> and <m>v</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow>  u'	 \amp =  v </mrow>
						<mrow>  v'	 \amp =  e^{t-3}\cos t + 2u  </mrow>
					</md>
					Note that we can also convert the initial conditions to the new variables:
					<md>
						<mrow> u(3)	 \amp =  -1 </mrow>
						<mrow> v(3)	 \amp =  0  </mrow>
					</md>
					Now we can use Euler's method as follows.
					<md>
						<mrow>  \mbox{Preliminaries:	}	\amp \amp	f_1(t,u,v)	 \amp =  v </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	f_2(t,u,v)	 \amp =  e^{t-3}\cos t +2u </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	h 	 \amp =  0.2 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		t_0	 \amp =  3 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		u_0	 \amp =  -1 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		v_0	 \amp =  0 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp \mbox{Iteration 1:}		\amp \amp	t_1	 \amp =  t_0 + h </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  3 + 0.2 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  3.2 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	u_1	 \amp =  u_0 + h \cdot f_1(t_0,u_0,v_0) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  -1 + 0.2 \cdot f_1(3, -1, 0) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  -1 + 0.2 \cdot [0] </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  -1 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	v_1	 \amp =  v_0 + h \cdot f_2(t_0,u_0,v_0) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  0 + 0.2 \cdot f_2(3, -1, 0) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  0 + 0.2 \cdot [e^{3-3}\cos(3) + 2(-1)] </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  -0.5980  </mrow>
					</md>
					Therefore <m>u(3.2) \approx -1 </m>, which means <m>y(3.2) \approx -1 </m> (and, even though we were not asked for it specifically, we also know <m>y'(3.2) \approx -0.5980 </m>).
				</p>
			</solution>
			<answer><p><m>y(3.2) \approx -1</m></p></answer>
		</exercise>

		<exercise>
			<title>Euler's Method</title>

			<statement>
				<p>
					Approximate <m>y(3.2)</m> if <m>y</m> is the solution to IVP:
					<md>
						y'' - 2y = e^{t-3} \cos t,\quad  y(3) = -1,\quad y'(3) = 0.
					</md>
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					We will use the system of DEs developed earlier and use Euler's method as follows:
					<md>
						<mrow>  \mbox{Preliminaries:	}	\amp \amp	f_1(t,u,v)	 \amp =  v </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	f_2(t,u,v)	 \amp =  e^{t-3}\cos t +2u </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	h	 \amp =  0.1 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	t_0	 \amp =  3 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	u_0	 \amp =  -1 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	v_0	 \amp =  0 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp \mbox{Iteration 1:}		\amp \amp	t_1	 \amp =  t_0 + h </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  3 + 0.1 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  3.1 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	u_1	 \amp =  u_0 + h \cdot f_1(t_0,u_0,v_0) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  -1 + 0.1 \cdot f_1(3, -1, 0) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  -1 + 0.1 \cdot [0] </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  -1 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	v_1	 \amp =  v_0 + h\cdot f_2(t_0,u_0,v_0) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  0 + 0.1 \cdot f_2(3, -1, 0) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  0 + 0.1 \cdot [e^{3-3}\cos(3) + 2(-1)] </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  -0.2990 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp \mbox{Iteration 2:}		\amp \amp	t_2	 \amp =  t_1 + h </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  3.1 + 0.1 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  3.2 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	u_2	 \amp =  u_1 + h \cdot f_1(t_1,u_1,v_1) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  -1 + 0.1 \cdot f_1(3.1, -1, -0.2990) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  -1 + 0.1 \cdot [-0.2990] </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  -1.0299 </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp	v_2	 \amp =  v_1 + h\cdot f_2(t_1,u_1,v_1) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  -0.2990 + 0.1 \cdot f_2(3.1, -1, -0.2990) </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  -0.2990 + 0.1 \cdot [e^{3.1 - 3}\cos(3.1) + 2(-1)] </mrow>
						<mrow>  \amp \amp		 \amp =  -0.6094  </mrow>
					</md>
					Therefore <m>u(3.2) \approx -1.0299 </m>, which means <m>y(3.2) \approx -1.0299 </m> (and, even though we were not asked for it specifically, we also know <m>y'(3.2) \approx -0.6094 </m>).
				</p>
			</solution>
			<answer><p><m>y(3.2) \approx -1.0299 </m></p></answer>
		</exercise>
	</exercises>
	
</section>
